TY  - JOUR
AU  - Pries, Michael J.
T1  - Persistence of Employment Fluctuations: A Model of Recurring Job Loss
PY  - 2004
Y1  - 2004/01/01
DO  - 10.1111/0034-6527.00281
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 71
IS  - 1
SP  - 193
EP  - 215
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - Standard models of employment fluctuations cannot reconcile the unemployment rate's remarkable persistence with the high job-finding rates found in worker flows data. A matching model emphasizing high hazard rates among newly formed firm-worker matches can resolve this shortcoming. In the model, matches are experience goods; consequently, newly employed workers face higher hazard rates. Following a job loss, workers may experience several short-lived jobs before finding stable employment. At an aggregate level, an initial burst of job loss precipitates a steady flow of recurring job loss. A simulation shows that this recurring job loss can account for the fact that the unemployment rate remains elevated for as much as 4 or 5 years following an initial jump.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0034-6527.00281
ER  - 



